How much does the performace of baseball players affect their salary?¶

Introduction / Motivation¶

Anybody who looks at the current salaries of the highest paid baseball players these days is immediately in awe. Max Scherzer recently set a record, making over 43 million dollars per year. Several players are making over 30 million, and over 50 MLB players are making at least 20 million dollars per year. Our work is an exploration into these salaries, seeing how much players really deserve such salaries. We will compare players to one another, taking note of how well they perform compared to other players, and how much money they make compared to other players. To learn more about the highest paid baseball players today, please look at https://www.nbcsports.com/washington/nationals/here-are-highest-paid-mlb-players-2022-season.

In this project, we will look both at batters and pitchers, comparing batters' salaries to other batters' salaries, and doing the same for pitchers. Our null hypothesis is that a player's performances has no affect on his salary. We hope to reject this null hypothesis, showing that there is indeed a correlation between these high-paid baseball players and their actual performace throughout the season.

Data Collection¶

In this section, we will collect data for the batters and pitchers. In order to get all of the information we need for each player, we will also need to gather information from the salaries data table. We will then combine the salaries with the batters as well as with pitchers in order to view each player and their salary in the same dataframe.

In this first section, we begin by gathering the data from these data sets, and limiting them to the years between 1985 and 2016. Unfortunately, we were not able to find salary data that went beyond the year 2016.

# Imports
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import datetime

# Gathering csv files and condensing to the 22 years between 1985 and 2016
data_batting = pd.read_csv("Batting.csv")
data_batting = data_batting[data_batting.yearID >= 1985][data_batting.yearID <= 2016]

data_pitching = pd.read_csv("Pitching.csv")
data_pitching = data_pitching[data_pitching.yearID >= 1985][data_pitching.yearID <= 2016]

data_salaries = pd.read_csv("Salaries.csv")
data_salaries = data_salaries[data_salaries.yearID >= 1985][data_salaries.yearID <= 2016]

data_people = pd.read_csv("People.csv")

# Condense the data to only include players playing between 1985 and 2016
data_people = data_people.dropna(subset = ['debut'])
def check_career(row) :
  if int(str(row['finalGame'])[:4]) <= 1985 or int(str(row['debut'])[:4]) >= 2016:
    return 'no'
  return 'yes'

data_people['career'] = data_people.apply (lambda row: check_career(row), axis=1)
data_people = data_people[data_people['career'] == 'yes']
data_people = data_people.drop(['birthYear', 'birthMonth', 'birthDay', 
                                'birthCountry', 'birthState', 'birthCity', 'deathYear', 'deathMonth', 'deathDay', 
                                'deathCountry', 'deathState', 'deathCity', 'weight', 'height'], axis=1)
data_people = data_people.reset_index()

# from pandas.tseries.offsets import YearEnd
# Create violin plot of HR by year

def round_down_5(row):
  n = row['yearID']
  return n//5*5

data_salaries['5_year_span_start'] = data_salaries.apply (lambda row: round_down_5(row), axis=1)

salaries = {}

for year in data_salaries['yearID'].unique():
  salaries[year] = 0

for index, row in data_salaries.iterrows():
  salaries[row.yearID] += row.salary

plt.bar(salaries.keys(), salaries.values())
plt.ylabel("Total Salary")
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.title("Total salary for each year")
plt.show()

Clearly the total salary is increasing per year. This means it would be pointless to compare salaries between years. We will thus treat each player's salary as a fraction of the total payroll for that year.

In [ ]:
def salary_fraction (row):
  return row.salary / salaries[row.yearID]

data_salaries['salary_fraction'] = data_salaries.apply (lambda row: salary_fraction(row), axis=1)

salaries_fractions = {}

for span in data_salaries['5_year_span_start'].unique():
  salaries_fractions[span] = []

for index, row in data_salaries.iterrows():
  salaries_fractions[row['5_year_span_start']].append(row.salary_fraction)

fig_res, ax_res = plt.subplots()
    
#Create the plot
ax_res.violinplot(salaries_fractions.values(),salaries_fractions.keys(),widths=4,showmeans=True)
ax_res.set_xlabel("5 Year Span Starting Year")
ax_res.set_ylabel("Fraction of the Total Salary")
ax_res.set_title("Salary of Each Player in Comparison to Total Payroll by Five Year Span")
Out[ ]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Salary of Each Player in Comparison to Total Payroll by Five Year Span')

We can see through this violin plot that relative to other players, each player has continued to be paid a similar amount. The overwhelming majority of players make around .001 of the total payroll, with the mean being around .0015 to .002 each year. This will be a better measure to use when comparing data throughout different years.

Now let's add that data to our batters dataframe.

Let's look at a couple key stats, and see how player who are paid over .002 of the total payroll do in those stats. We are going to look specifically at OPS, batting average, and home runs. Since OPS does not exist in our dataset, we will calculate it manually.

In [ ]:
def ops (row):
  slugging = (row['H'] + row['2B'] + 2 * row['3B'] + 3 * row['HR']) / row['AB']
  OBP = (row['BB'] + row['IBB'] + row['HBP'] + row['H']) / (row['AB'] + row['BB'] + row['IBB'] + row['SH'] + row['SF'] + row['HBP'])
  return slugging + OBP

data_all['OPS'] = data_all.apply (lambda row: ops(row), axis = 1)

data_all['AVG'] = data_all['H'] / data_all['AB']

Let's create an interaction term for these three stats so we can do some regression analysis.

In [ ]:
stat_means = {}
for stat in ['OPS', 'AVG', 'HR']:
  player_stats = {}
  stat_means[stat] = {}

  for span in data_all['5_year_span_start'].unique():
    player_stats[span] = data_all.loc[data_all['5_year_span_start'] == span, stat].mean()
    stat_means[stat][span] = data_all.loc[data_all['5_year_span_start'] == span, stat].mean()

def get_interaction (row):
  span = row['5_year_span_start']
  norm_ops = row['OPS'] / stat_means['OPS'][span]
  norm_avg = row['AVG'] / stat_means['AVG'][span]
  norm_hr = row['HR'] / stat_means['HR'][span]
  return (norm_ops + norm_avg + norm_hr) / 3


# data['interaction_term'] = data.apply(lambda row: get_interaction(row), axis = 1)
data_all['interaction_term'] = data_all.apply(lambda row: get_interaction(row), axis = 1)

# data

from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
import numpy as np

y = np.array(data_all['interaction_term']).reshape(-1,1)
x = np.array(data_all['salary_fraction']).reshape(-1,1)

#Initialize and fit the model
reg = LinearRegression()
reg.fit(x, y)

plt.plot(x, reg.predict(x))

plt.scatter(data_all['salary_fraction'], data_all['interaction_term'])
plt.xlabel("Salary Fraction")
plt.ylabel("Interaction Term")
plt.title("Salary for each player by interaction term")

plt.show()
In [ ]:
# compute with formulas from the theory
yhat = reg.predict(x)
SS_Residual = sum((y-yhat)**2)       
SS_Total = sum((y-np.mean(y))**2)     
r_squared = 1 - (float(SS_Residual))/SS_Total
adjusted_r_squared = 1 - (1-r_squared)*(len(y)-1)/(len(y)-x.shape[1]-1)
print(r_squared, adjusted_r_squared)

[0.18754587] [0.18747837]

Conclusions:

There is clearly a difference between the players paid a high amount and those not (see original bar graphs). However, there is a lot of variance within these highly paid players. This is most likely due to the fact that stats are very similar, and small changes can make big differences. Any player playing slightly better than expected can have a big impact, so the players paid a lot, though expected to do very well, might just do well.

In [ ]:
def round_down_0005(row):
  n = row['salary_fraction'] * 10000
  return n // 5 * 5 / 10000

data_all['salary_bracket'] = data_all.apply (lambda row: round_down_0005(row), axis=1)
# data['salary_bracket'] = data.apply (lambda row: round_down_0005(row), axis=1)

brackets = {}

for brack in data_all['salary_bracket'].unique():
  brackets[brack] = data_all.loc[data_all['salary_bracket'] == brack, 'interaction_term'].mean()


x = np.array(list(brackets.keys())).reshape(-1,1)
y = np.array(list(brackets.values())).reshape(-1,1)

#Initialize and fit the model
reg1 = LinearRegression()
reg1.fit(x, y)

plt.plot(x, reg1.predict(x))

plt.scatter(brackets.keys(), brackets.values())
plt.xlabel("Salary Fraction")
plt.ylabel("Interaction Term")
plt.title("Average interaction term by salary bracket")

plt.show()
In [ ]:
# compute with formulas from the theory
yhat = reg1.predict(x)
SS_Residual = sum((y-yhat)**2)       
SS_Total = sum((y-np.mean(y))**2)     
r_squared = 1 - (float(SS_Residual))/SS_Total
print(r_squared)

[0.79566675]

We see a huge amount of correlation between the salary bracket and the interaction term. This can help us predict which salary bracket a player will be in.

In [ ]:
def predicted_salary (year, interaction_term):
  return (reg.coef_[0][0] * year + reg.intercept_[0]) * (reg1.coef_[0][0] * interaction_term + reg1.intercept_[0])

# Merging all career lengths to associated pitchers
pitchers = pd.merge(data_pitching, data_people, on='playerID', how='inner')

# Merging all salaries to associated pitchers
pitchers = pd.merge(pitchers, data_salaries, on=['playerID','yearID'], how="inner")
 
# Only accounting for pitchers playing for at least 5 years since they will have signed a larger contract
pitchers['career_length'] = pitchers.apply (lambda row: row['yearID'] - int(str(row['debut'])[:4]), axis=1)
pitchers = pitchers[pitchers.career_length >= 5]

# Pitchers who appeared in a substantial amount of games
pitchers = pitchers[pitchers.G > 30]

pitchers = pitchers.dropna(subset = ['salary'])

pitchers['star'] = pitchers.apply (lambda row: 'All-Star' if row['salary_fraction'] > 0.004 else 'Non-All-Star', axis=1)
stat_avg = {}
for stat in ['BB%', 'SO%', 'BAOpp', 'ERA', 'IPouts']:
  stat_avg[stat] = []
  player_stats = {}
  player_stats_stars = {}
  for span in pitchers['5_year_span_start'].unique():
    year_mean = pitchers.loc[pitchers['5_year_span_start'] == span, stat].mean()
    stat_avg[stat].append(year_mean)
    year_mean_stars = pitchers.loc[(pitchers['5_year_span_start'] == span) & (pitchers['salary_fraction'] > 0.004), stat].mean()
    player_stats[span] = year_mean
    player_stats_stars[span] = year_mean_stars

  plt.bar(player_stats.keys(), player_stats.values(), 4, label = "All Players")
  plt.bar(player_stats.keys(), player_stats_stars.values(), 1, label = "High Salaries")
  plt.ylabel("Average " + stat)
  plt.xlabel("Year")
  plt.title("Comparing average " + stat + " for each year")
  plt.legend()
  plt.show()
  
# Interaction - avg k% + ip% -  bb% - era% - oppBA%
In [ ]:
def interaction(row) :
  year = row['5_year_span_start']
  if year == 1985 :
    index = 0
  elif year == 1990 :
    index = 1
  elif year == 1995 :
    index = 2
  elif year == 2000 :
    index = 3
  elif year == 2005 :
    index = 4
  elif year == 2010 :
    index = 5
  elif year == 2015 :
    index = 6
  
  k_avg = row['SO%'] / stat_avg['SO%'][index]
  bb_avg = row['BB%'] / stat_avg['BB%'][index]
  era = row['ERA'] / stat_avg['ERA'][index]
  baopp = row['BAOpp'] / stat_avg['BAOpp'][index]
  inn = row['IPouts'] / stat_avg['IPouts'][index]

  return k_avg - bb_avg - era - baopp + inn

pitchers['interaction_term'] = pitchers.apply(lambda row: interaction(row), axis = 1)
